# TypeScript Guidelines

## Basic Principles
- Use English for all code and documentation
- Always declare types for variables and functions (avoid `any`)
- Use JSDoc to document public classes and methods
- Don't leave blank lines within functions
- One export per file

## Nomenclature
- **Classes**: PascalCase (e.g., `ComicCard`, `UserService`)
- **Variables/Functions**: camelCase (e.g., `getComics`, `userSettings`)
- **Files/Directories**: kebab-case (e.g., `comic-card.tsx`, `user-settings.ts`)
- **Constants**: UPPERCASE (e.g., `ENCRYPTION_CHAPTER_KEY`)
- **Boolean variables**: Start with verbs (e.g., `isLoading`, `hasError`, `canDelete`)

## Functions
- Write short functions with single purpose (< 20 instructions)
- Use verbs for function names (e.g., `getComics`, `updateUser`)
- Boolean functions: `isX`, `hasX`, `canX` (e.g., `isAuthenticated`)
- Action functions: `executeX`, `saveX` (e.g., `saveComic`)
- Avoid nesting blocks with early returns and utility functions
- Use higher-order functions (map, filter, reduce)
- Use arrow functions for simple functions (< 3 instructions)
- Use default parameters instead of null/undefined checks

## Data Types
- Don't abuse primitive types, encapsulate in composite types
- Use `readonly` for immutable data
- Use `as const` for literal constants
- Create interfaces for object contracts

## Classes
- Follow SOLID principles
- Prefer composition over inheritance
- Write small classes (< 200 instructions, < 10 public methods)
- Declare interfaces to define contracts

## Error Handling
- Use exceptions for unexpected errors
- Catch exceptions to fix problems, add context, or use global handler

## Examples from Codebase
```typescript
// Good: Typed function with clear naming
export const getComics = async (query: QueryComics): Promise<Comic[]> => {
  const result = await backendService.get<Comic[]>('/comics', query);
  if (result.kind === 'ok') {
    return result.data;
  }
  throw new Error(formatError(result));
};

// Good: Boolean variable naming
const { isLoading, hasError } = useComics(query);

// Good: Interface definition
export interface Comic {
  id: number;
  title: string;
  authors: Author[];
  // ...
}
```
